title: DIY FPV goggles
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I bought the Eachine EV800 FPV goggles and I was not completely happy with the goggles-part. It was uncomfortable and I was not able the wear my regular glasses under them. Therefore I started to design my own goggle-part.

I started with making a four part assembly in SketchUp to snap into the existing mount on the EV800, and also to hold the fresnel-lense in place. I 3D printed the parts, glued them together, and they fit perfectly. Since the shape of the rest of the goggles is very complicated, I thought it would be very time-consuming to design and 3D print everything. Therefore I built the rest of the goggles using cardboard, paper and hot glue. To make it look better and be more comfortable to wear I covered the entire thing in fabric, using more hot glue. I kept the part touching the face as large as possible to make them fit over my glasses. I finished off the design with some 3D printed parts to mount the original head strap from the EV800. I am pretty satisfied with the result. Now the goggles are comfortable, fits over my glasses, and is comfortable to wear. And I can still remove the screen from the goggles is I want.

More detail images are available on my website: http://axelsdiy.brinkeby.se/?p=1415#more-1415

title: Glue Spreader for Glass Bed
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
My preference for print surface is a glass bed and I use PVA wood glue diluted with 50% water when a bit extra adhesion is required. I was getting sick of spreading the glue with my fingers; - it doesn't produce a nice even coat, and I got sick of sticky fingers.

So I decided to print something that I can use to spread the glue onto the bed easily and evenly. My 'Glue Spreader' is a very simple design that took about 5 minutes to create in Fusion 360. It works really well. A blob of glue on the bed, and a twist and swipe leaves a nice even and smooth layer of glue.

Printer:

Anet A8

Notes:

The default size of 100mm is probably bigger than you need it. I have scaled it down to 70% (70mm) diameter. This size works well on a 200x200 bed.

The print pictured was printed from Copper PLA-Steel (supplied by 3DFillies in Melbourne). This filament requires no glue and so the print has a perfectly flat glass finish on the bottom - perfect for the task.

comments.text: You could just use cheap aquanet hairspray on the glass and not have to worry about how to spread glue and get the best adhesion possible.

I certainly don't want better adhesion - the glue is often too good (which is why i dilute it). Plus i don't like spraying it direct onto the printer, and removing the glass each time is certainly not easy. With the glue spreader using glue is easy and provides the perfect amount of adhesion.

title: SmartAlu 80mm hotbed post-printing cooling fan support

description.text:
The SmartAlu aluminium hotbed is amazing (the printed pieces stick perfectly on it, it requires no glue or adhesive tape of any sort, and as soon as it's cooled down, the pieces are really easy to remove), but it's also amazingly slow to cool down after each printing.

To resolve this issue, I installed a 80mm cooling fan (the regular 12V kind that's really easy to get), and designed a two-pieces very simple support that holds it with the best orientation, and it works wonderfully : the cooling down time is reduced by a significant amount! :)

To give you and idea of its efficiency, my tests show that, in a room at 20°C, without this device, the hot bed goes from 60° to 25° in no less than 20 minutes. With this cooling device, going from 60° to 25° takes only 5.30 minutes!

To install the fan on the support you'll need four M4x12 bolts and nuts.
You can also use bolts to install the support on the bottom aluminium plate of the printer, but two-sided adhesive tape will be just as much efficient with less trouble. ;)

The general idea is just to put it in the middle of the X-axis, and at the back of the printer (without touching the Z axis!), so that when the plate is at its lowest position just above it, the fan points directly at the middle of the plate.

Then comes the wiring part…

For that, you'll need a Ramps1.4 RRD Fan Extender, that goes on the "Servos" of the MKS-Gen board (that's between "5V out" and "Aux-1").
All wiring information is detailed here : http://www.instructables.com/id/Configuring-and-using-Reprap-Ramps14-RRD-Fan-Exten/

…and the coding part :

For that, start by checking your new fan is connected properly, by sending the following command through the terminal to your printer :
M42 P11 S255
If it starts blowing, you have a winner! :)
Turn it off with :
M42 P11 S0.

Then modify your custom ending G-code so that, at the end of the printing, the plate will get down as low as possible without (of course) hitting the fan or the filament spool.

For instance, it would be something like :
G1 Z170 ; get the plate as low as possible above the cooling fan.
(on my Smartalu, for instance, this is the optimal height)

Then add these lines at the very end of your custom end G-code :
M42 P11 S255 ; turn hot bed fan on !
M190 R25 ; wait for the hot bed to cool down to 25°C…
M42 P11 S0 ;…then turn the fan off !
M140 S0 ; and turn the hot bed completely off

This way, this cooling device will start automatically at the end of each printing, and keep doing so until the printing plate has cooled down to 25° (or any other temperature would be sufficient to allow you to remove the printed pieces easily), then turn off.

description.text:
I wanted to mount an Insteon Mini Remote without making any screw holes in my kitchen cabinet so I designed this bracket. It's intended to fit current production Leviton single gang switchplates. Unlike the standard Insteon mini-remote mount, the wall-facing surface is closed and large enough to use two 3M Command strips for mounting.

The switchplate screws self-tap into the bracket. I cut the switchplate screws by 1-1/2 turns so they didn't dig into the cabinet. To complete the disguise I tucked the tails of the Command strips under the switchplate. Looks just like the real thing.

I also included a narrow version that should work with other types of switchplates, but I haven't tested this one. YMMV.

Check out my other Insteon things:

If you want to mount over an existing box you might like my Insteon Mini Remote Bracket for Existing Boxes https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2834485.

If you want the original style Mini Remote mount check out my Insteon Mini Remote Wall Mount Bracket p/n 2444B4 https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2834483.

I am not responsible for any damage to your boat or loss of property (fenders). Use these hangers at your own risk

Enjoy!!

description.text:
This is a version of the HPD F1 to use a Lexan Body. Also the front and middle is redesigned. The front is stronger and middle part takes the battery 90 deg rotated.
It is compatible with the rear cradle but there is also a cradle that you build from several parts included, it is not as strong but easier to change individual parts and less waste of plastic when things break. The rear cradle is compatible with the original HPD version but there is also a wide version for this wider body and side_stabs are 2 different versions depending on combinations.

The car was designed to be printed in Nylon like 910 that is slightly rigid. But my prototype I made with prima value PLA did not break so it is very strong with PLA apart from the wings.

I strongly recommend to print the front wing in Bridge Nylon or something with similar flex. Rear wing I have used Bridge Nylon and it flex good and never breaks.

If you want to go cheap or cant find springs, I have used the spring from a ball pen and cut it to shorter length for front. And for rear you can ignore the side springs completely if you just want to go racing and print the plastic main rear spring that is included.

All parts is made in OpenSCAD and source is at github: https://github.com/condac/hpdf1_lexan
Talk with us on Google+ https://plus.google.com/u/0/communities/117625327650679845498
Or in the OpenR/C Facebook site https://www.facebook.com/groups/OpenRCProject/

Printer:

Home made RepRap style

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15 or similar

Infill:

100%

Notes:

All parts are designed to print in 100% infill for strength.

Rear Axle

(The rear axle is still a bit unreliable and under development, changes will be made)
The rear axle parts in this is for carbon fiber rods.
M4 threaded rod 167mm
Carbon fiber rod OD 8mm ID 6mm 120mm
Carbon fiber rod OD 6mm ID 4mm 120mm

Alternative any other rods with same dimention or a 8mm rod with 4mm inner diameter.

Cut carbon fiber rods to 120mm (longer is better than shorter, a longer axle can be compensated with washers, a shorter is useless)
You need 2 rods one 8mm outer diameter and one 6mm outer diameter both with 1mm thickness so you can slide the 6mm rod into the 8mm rod and then the M4 rod inside. And then glue them all together with the M4 sticking out 22mm on the right side (diff side).

Place one regular M4 nut on the diff side with a washer between the nut and rods. The washer must be smaller than 8mm OD so bearings can slide over it. If you don't have washers that fit just ignore them. Don't tighthen the nut because this will break the glue inside. The nut is just there to take stress off the glue in case you crash or the glue fails.

On the other side where we just want a wheel to fit place a <8mm washer if you have it and then 2 M4 Lock nuts placed with the nylon locking side towards each other. Do not tighten the nuts towards the rod to hard. Tighten the nuts against each other. These nuts will transfer all the torque from the axle to the wheel so tighten it hard against each other will make it stay in place. It will want to get loose on braking if your wheel nut is loose. Acceleration will make it self tightening so there is very little chance of it coming loose during driving.

Last glue the indrive in place. Best way to place the indrive right is to screw on a extra m4 nut on the diff side and assemble everything with gears diffplates and diff balls and you will see where the indrive want to be placed. The extra M4 nut creates a perfect space inside, and when you remove it after gluing the indrive in place you will have a gap between the wheel and axle where it can rotate free.

Non-Printed parts needed
  • Low-profile servo
  • ESC + Motor
  • Shorty LiPo-Pack
  • 5pcs MR128-2RS Bearing
  • 4pcs MR105-2RS Bearing
  • 10pcs 3.175mm (1/8") Diff Balls
  • 2pcs M14 28 1.5mm washer
  • 170mm M4 threaded rod
  • Carbon fiber rod OD 8mm ID 6mm 120mm (Note: All carbon fiber rods must be able to slide into each other)
  • Carbon fiber rod OD 6mm ID 4mm 120mm
  • Carbon fiber rod OD 10mm ID 8mm 120mm ( for future upgrade, still in development )
  • 3pcs M3 Locknuts
  • ~4pcs Mx6 button screws
  • ~18pcs M3x10 button screws

This ia a 1 cm thick case to replace the standard thick design of the Mocrosaft 3000 /pro webcam. A fine compact HD(720p) webcam which you can still buy for under 25 euro. I like this cam because it works ok in most os-s like raspbian on PI, linux, freebsd. Incuding reasonable quality sound.
This one is running for monitoring print-jobs on my Wanhao D4. To get it working i mounted a Pi(1) plus a cheap icidu usb2 hub. On the Pi i installed Astrobox (great render service).
Everything is powered by adding 2 Traco powerconverters (whatever input to 5v 1A max).
See photo's. The traco power converters are not cheapest you can get (9 euro) but don't need extra cooling or condensators for noise etc.... so you can safely solder them on a wire from power supply to input on Pi or other 5v device... easy.
The powerconverters are mounted on the psu next to the Pi (with the ASTRO sd).

Make sure when printing a full printbed the carriage is not touching the camera. When your printer is assembled like mine the end-stop for Y-direction leaves a space of +/- 12 mm! between platformguides and carriage. So i can reach all without a collision.
Too check go to jogmode in menu and move Z (bed) to top and home the X and Y. After that disable the steppers and move the carriage along cam by hand.

Roadhog is my favorite Overwatch character and it seemed there was a general lack of this specific Overwatch prop, so I thought I'll give it a go. Very happy with the finished product here. Would love your feedback so I can make improvements if needed. This was simple to design this initially and so painstaking to get a lot of the details right.

I haven't mentioned this previously, but all of the models I release are cut into parts that can fit onto a standard hobbyist printer with a build space of 6"x6"x6".
I didn't bother adding joints this version, or holes for a rod, sanding each part and just super gluing it all together should be fine for a cosplay piece.
The exclusion of the tape is purposeful. I figured that it would be easier and more realistic if people who print this use old hockey tape or wrap bandages. Also I recommend picking up a plastic chain from a Halloween store to finish the piece.

Edit: Apparently Simplify3d deals with Blender exported stl's differently than Cura, which is what I usually use. I have had the complaint on a few of my designs that they are not scaled. So I did some investigating and experimenting wit the program, and apparently you need to set the scale factor to 1000 when exporting out of blender so the dimensions to come out right in Simplify3D. So sorry for the trouble everyone. Lesson learned. From now on all my designs wil feature the 2 different scales depending on the slicer you use, and I am going to update all my old models.

Enjoy everyone! If you do please leave a like, or subscribe to my page. I plan on releasing lots more and hope to keep bumping up the quality.

Cheers!

I didn't like how the wires were only held by the kapton tape and solder joints on the heater pcb at the back of the bed on my Anycubic Prusa i3 clone so I made this strain relief. It's designed to lead the wires 90° around the sides so they would move along next to the Y axis instead of above it.

Mounting is easy: Turn your bed around so the wires are sticking out to the left, then hold this part where it should go and drill 3mm holes using the holes in the print as a guide (they are spaced 20mm apart). comments.text: All Mesoamerican people shared the same calendar, Mayans, Aztecs, Zapotecs, etc. This calendar was developed by the Olmeca people around the 5th century BCE and then used by everybody en Mesoamerica. It is actually two calendars, a religious one where each day has at the same time one name and one number. There were 20 names and 13 numbers (from 1 to 13) giving a 260 days cycle. They had another calendar with 18 months of 20 days (from 0 to 19), 360 days, plus 5 days of bad luck, a total of 365 days. There were no leap years, so the seasons shifted one day each four years. A day required both dates and the same combination of both dates repeated at 18,980 days intervals, 52 years of 365 days each. With this system it was extremely difficult to know which (double calendar) date was before another date. It doesn't worked for longer periods and they invented a third calendar, the long count. There were 5 numbers for each long count date, from right to left the first number represented a day (0 to 19), the second one was a month (0 to 17), the third was a year (0 to 19) the fourth a 20 years period (0 to 19) and the fifth an 400 years period (0 to 13). According to the Mesoamercans, when the five number long count ends, a new cycle starts, no doomsday at all (that's a story for tourists). There were more numbers to represent longer periods, but seldom used.

A little project at the request of my spouse. She was admiring my 3D printed holders for my wax carving tools and files. However, the holes were too small for the things she wanted to hold. I was tasked with creating holders with larger holes.
The first one was using three holes with a hole design diameter of 12mm. I “project named” it the TriHolder. A square sided cube wouldn’t be aesthetic so I created some curves on two sides. They widen the base and make it look a bit better.
From the beginning the plan was to stretch it to six holes, which created the HexHolder. The wider base adds more stability and the extra holes provide added capacity.
The usual (very) rough sketch moved me to creating the designs in Autodesk Fusion 360. The renderings are directly from the program. I played with the idea of a curved top but I decided to KISS. Just two curved sides makes them easy to place side by side for more capacity.
I print mine at 0.20mm layer height with 4 layers top and bottom. The shell is three layers. Infill is 15% and could be a bit less. A lot of strength is not required. 15% is just enough for me to get a decent solid 4 ply layer at the bottom of the 12mm holes and the top of the holder.

This is a hand (or foot or hammer) tool designed to press 608 bearings into and out of things (like fidget spinners). It prevents damage to the bearing caused by excessive force to the inner race. The install press will press the bearing flush, but can't press past flush. The removal sleeve fits over the install press tip and allows you to press bearings out. The install tool alone also makes a great bearing cap removal tool for those really stuck caps!

I first uploaded only the install tool. Folks seemed to like it, so I designed a removal sleeve and a base (to allow the bearing to pop out) to go along with the install tool. Now it's a fully featured 608 bearing multi-tool!

The install tool may work with other 8mm inner diameter bearings.

Cross section of tool and bearing Revolve a profile, tweak some surfaces

This part was designed in a handful of steps. First I brought in a bearing model from McMaster. Then a sketch was created and revolved to make the overall shape. Finally, I used the chamfer, fillet, and draft tools to get the geometry I wanted on the bearing interface side.

While the first version was functional, the design saw three iterations. First to better capture the bearing on the center post, and then last to change the geometry for a cleaner print on the bearing interface side.

The removal sleeve and base were designed in the same manner, but only took one iteration as I had already dialed in the fits.

description.text:
This is the casing to a vibration sensing, automatic lighting unit for my Lima Junior Coach units. I wanted to be able to light the inside of my coaches, but didnt want to run it off track voltage (in this case DC) and am not going to switch this layout to DCC yet. The answer was a microcontroller based unit that could sense vibration and turn on the lights for a set amount of time. This 3D print is the cover for the controller and battery that hangs under the coach. It also gives the coaches a more realistic look as most coaches have various boxes under them.

I have updated this with the clamp to hold the battery in. I found it useful to drill the holes out by hand before turning in very fine screws to prevent splitting, as the object walls are quite thin.

title: Mini Table Saw v3 - Four Gears
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Mini Hand Powered Table Saw v3 - Four Gears

This is the Four Geared version of my Mini Hand Powered Table Saw. The gear ratio is in this one is about 1:3 so for every turn of the crank you make, the blade will rotate 3 turns. It spins faster than the first two versions but it is not as strong and gears will pop out of place if it encounters too much resistance.

This version makes some improvements over the other two versions. By using four gears instead of just two, I didn't need to have one gear sticking through the top like in the previous version. The two extra gears are mounted between a special arch and one of the sides of the table. I also redesigned it so I could remove of all the outside washers where the cranks went through the sides. It is a much cleaner look.

Like the previous 2 versions, I printed everything without supports except the Crank assembly and the Top. My Monoprice Select Mini printer was even able to print the Table Bottom without supports, though just barely. Some of the layers began curling under before it was able to bridge the gap and close the tops of the largest openings.

The half circle opening in the Crank is the hardest to clean out. I eventually added a drop of glue to keep it on the Crank shaft otherwise it would fall off after rigorous cranking.

When attempting to cut something, the Table should be held in place with a small clamp or a second pair of helpful hands.

Check out the video to see it in action. https://youtu.be/9sZSOpMYHnE

You can find the v1 Direct Drive version here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2430760
And the v2 Two Gear version here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2430770

Printer:

Notes:

ASSEMBLY INSTRUCTIONS (See Exploded View Picture)

Parts may need some clean up for the pieces to fit together. The Blade, Largest Gear and Smallest Gear should fit tightly on their shafts while the two middle size Gears and their Washers should be a looser fit.

You need to print two of the Small Shafts and four of the Washers.

Set the Table Bottom in front of you so the "arch" part inside is on the right.

Put each of the two middle size Gears onto a Short Shaft with a Washer and put them into place between the right Side and the Arch. Put each middle sized Gear onto a small shaft with a Washer on each side of it. The bigger of the two medium size Gears should be placed into the Table Bottom first. It goes in the lowest set of holes. The smaller of the two middle Gears goes in next and fits into the two holes farthest from you on the Arch. These two Gears are a bit of a pain to get in so just be careful and go slow because too much pressure on the Arch could snap it off.

Add the Handle over the thin part of the Crank. This should fit tightly enough not to come off but loose enough that you can turn it in place.

Slide the Large Gear onto the Crank Shaft and then from inside the Table Bottom, angle the end with the Large Gear into the hole closest to you on the right and snap the other end into the opening on the left.

Slide the Smallest Gear and the Blade onto the Blade Shaft and then angle the end with the Small Gear into the Table Bottom into the last hole on the right and slide the other end down into the hole on the left.

Add the Table Top. If needed, the Blade and Gears can all be adjusted along the shafts.

And you are ready to go!

description.text:
This here is DartKrafts remix of the BlasterforgePH Nerf Longshot Top Rail of which were kind enough to give to the community. But alas, the community do not have enormous printers!

So DartKrafts took it upon their crafty little fingers and split it up into printable parts for the masses.

It has 5 parts +2. Front End Piece, Front Left, Front Right, Back Left, Back Right, plus two little joiner thingies.

4 M3 x 12mm black self-tapping screws are required. Just steal some from your large size mellow yellow Nerf blaster (Stampede, Longshot front gun etc)

The joiner thingies were left separate intentionally as designing them into the rail pieces would put them right on 200mm, a common print bed size for most. The joiners are marked with a 'T' meaning 'Top' as the height and width may look the same, but no, good sirs and madams, they are not. So insert the joiner with the 'T' facing... the top of the rail.

Please glue the joiners into the 'Back' pieces first. The front pieces have an 11mm recess and the back have 10mm. The Joiners are 20mm. If you glue them into the front first you will end up with only 9mm to glue into the back. It was designed to have a 1mm gap in the Front pieces to make sure to allow for any tolerances being over and so the two parts could still come together snuggly. Dont worry about epoxy, just super glue em, but work fast as they are a tight fit and will bond hard just about instantly. If you feel safer with epoxy given the extra working time, then go for it, knock yourself out!

Tested and fitted. Works a treat. Bon Appetite!!

description.text:
This is a mount for a Runcam Split Camera and an Eachine TX02 Transmitter. I made it so that I could easily mount it (and un-mount it!) to my Hubsan H501S and H501A quad. Obviously it will work for a lot of other quads. If you look close and compare the STL file to the pictures, you will see that I've updated the STL to decrease weight a little more and leave a little more room for the battery while no longer needing a separate standoff for the antenna as it's now part of the print.

Why? Well, where I fly has way way way more trees than open area and the Hubsans look out, not down. With the Runcam, I can set it (before flight) to look down at whatever angle I feel like and get both FPV video and HD recording (with very good WDR!).

What's my setup for the quad? I drew up and 3D printed this part that everything mounts to. It mounts to the quad with two Reusable Releasable Zip Ties. It takes a whole... 30 seconds to attach or detach the setup. I elected to run it from a 350maH lipo since I have a bunch of them and they are more than enough for a 15 minute flight. So...

  1. Runcam Split
  2. Eachine TX02
  3. 350 maH battery
  4. 3D printed plate
  5. Velcro strap to hold battery on
  6. Two releasable zip ties
  7. 3 zip ties to hold TX02 and antenna on
  8. 4 nylon screws and 12 nylon nuts
  9. 1 losi connector to connect TX02 to Runcam PCB

What do I lose? About 25% of my flying time with the extra 51g of weight. On average (since I don't fly it to LVC), I drop from 16 minutes of flight time to 12 plus a few seconds of flight time.

What do I gain? Heck, I wanted both of these Quads to use as a "relatively" inexpensive AP platform. Being able to fly slowly over any given area and accurately line up shots is great. The ability to fly over the trees and spot things here and there is also fantastic.

I put a 7" monitor (my trusty dusty Boscam 5802) on a tripod in front of me. That way I get the forward video and telemetry from the transmitter and the view of the area below from the 7" monitor. Or when I fly the 501A from my phone for it's very nice waypoint setup, then forward video and telemetry from the phone and the view of the area below from the 7" monitor. Win/win!

Designed to be cut from 1/8" plywood. Acrylic may have an issue with the snap-tabs that hold the ends on, but may work ok. The "red" layer is not to be cut all the way though, it's only a "marking pass". On our 40W 5th Gen I setup the cut like this:

Assembly

Connect the ends to the longer piece. Both ends should point "up". Attach the end with the hole so the words face away from the other end. Attach the remaining end. The ends should snap into place, it may take some encouragement to get them to fit.

Cutting, usage, warnings, etc.

This piece is designed to be cut out of 1/8" thick material. I have only tested it with baltic birch plywood, any 1/8" hobby/craft wood should work fine. The snap tabs that hold the ends on may not work well with acrylic, but if someone wants to try it then who knows.

Firstly, NEVER point your telescope towards the sun without an appropriate solar filter fully installed. Also, any other finder scopes must be covered over or removed as well so the sun can not reach them. Attempting to view the sun without a proper solar filter installed will cause PERMANENT BLINDNESS. Additionally, it will likely damage your telescope. The same goes for finder scopes - even if you don't intend to use the optical finder scope, the sun may damage it if you don't cover it up or remove it first.

The Sol Finder is installed with the "hole" end towards the sun. Install it on your TELRAD base by inserting the bottoms of the ends into the mounting holes of the base. Turn the thumb screws down - note that you will have to make sure the screws make contact with the wood.

To use: Point towards the sun. You can use the shadow of the front of the finder to do the "rough" alignment, move the telescope around until the shadow completely covers the rear target side (rear) of the finder. A small white dot will appear on the target end, align this to the center of the target. This gives your precise alignment allowing you to line your telescope up with the sun.

Install, align, view, and enjoy!

description.text:
I was looking for a way to mount my FrSky X4R-SB RX and TBS Unify Pro HV (Race) VTX to my Armattan Chameleon frame without using any zipties, and after a lot of revision and redesigns (because of things like not testing the designs with props on and finding out your atennas will be clipped straight away if you just point the upwards when coming out the back), they have evolved into this collection of parts that i am now using on my build.

  • The RX mount is held in place by the two posts of the aluminium rear part of the frame. The antenna of an X4R-SB can be passed through the mount out the back, where it has 3mm holes for antenna tubes. It also has a groove in the side wall, through which the cables for an LED strip can be routed to the LED bumper (see below).
  • The VTX mount sits on top of the RX mount and is locked in place with a bolt through the square hole next to the VTX antenna mounting hole. The VTX Lock is just my fancy name for square washer to keep the VTX mount from sliding out, and it should work with any M3 bolt. Just make sure it is long enough to screw deep enough into the VTX mount, but not too long to stick too far out the other end.
    I am also providing a rectangular VTX antenna washer that should be attached to the VTX antenna pigtail, so that it sits between the connector's tabs and the frame, to keep the antenna from wiggling around.
  • The LED bumper was designed to allow an Adafruit Neopixel Stick to be attached to it, but it may work with other LED boards, like cheap chinese clones. You will need two M2 bolts to attach the LED board, preferably something short like the ones provided with the frame.
  • The beeper clip gets clipped to the front of the frame, so that the beeper sits right behind the FPV camera, pointing downwards. You will be limited in what angles you can tilt your FPV camera, but it works reasonably fine with my Runcam Swift 2. The clip will fit a 12mm diameter beeper.

There are cutouts in both the RX and VTX mounts to give you access to the respective board's buttons and onboard LEDs.

If you are not using the Armattan PDB, which puts the XT60 connector on the side of the frame, you will need to route your battery lead out the front, e.g. between the stack and the camera cage (or any other way you see fit), as the holes in the back are used for fixing the mounts to the frame.

Regarding the TBS Unify Pro versions, the HV and HV Race have the same dimensions and should both fit just fine, but the non-HV one (v2) is a bit smaller. It should still fit, but you will have to check if it isn't wiggling around too much.

Important! You probably know this already if you have the Chameleon frame and tried fitting the stock Unify Pro pigtail connector into the hole in the rear, but for those who don't: You will need to grind/sand/cut off one of the tabs on the connector, otherwise you won't be able to screw the upper plate onto the standoff. This is not specific to my mounts, you will have to do that either way.

description.text:
The BT260 replica on display here is a classic hostile world exploration and fighting vehicle. It is powered by a Smith and Westor Nuke generator, and has a unique wheeled track system, made up of multiple independently suspended and powered dual wheels. They can each turn and in case of mine (or other) damage can be retracted or even jettisoned. The Cata drive allows it to traverse much terrain other vehicles cannot, although the top speed is fairly low at only 60kmh.
The gun system can fire 122mm Berkerlian Darts for use against other armoured vehicles and bunkers, or also a mini nuke lob thrower to exterminate the enemy in a 500m radius. Sometimes they also carry standard HE rounds, to use when friendlies are nearby. Co-axle to the main guns is a rapid fire 25mm cannon which is useful for ranging and suppression fire.
The tank has a crew of two, one commander/gunner and a driver/engineer. The rear airlock hatch is the only entry point, and the upper hatch cannot be opened. Much of the inside of the vehicle is open and the vehicle can sometimes carry a small three man squad and their weapons, or two stretchers.
A spare wheel pod is carried on the right side, along with the nuke generator. The vehicle has no dedicated shield generator, unlike latter vehicles of this series, and many regard this as a major failing. Some BT260s were converted with a shield generator fitted and these are sometimes called the BT260 Type G, but are rare and sometimes only used for command vehicles.
The tanks (although technically not a tank, the common and current definition of this word includes these common wheeled vehicles), were used extensively by the Federation, and some found their way to the independent edge colonies. There have been several major battles between mainly BT260 tanks the more modern BT700 tanks as the Federation moved to re-establish its justified dominance throughout this galaxy arm.

description.text:
A push-fit socket for those semi-standardized garden hose quick connect things for 3/4" garden hose threads. It uses 6mm airgun bullets as latches. IT ACTUALLY WORKS AND HOLDS PRESSURE WITHOUT LEAKING though tolerances may depend on your printer, I printed it on a Taz 6. Please read the instructions.

Requires vitamins: 4 x 6mm plastic airgun bullets (i.e. airsoft), ABS glue.
Requires cleanup after printing.

LulzBot

TAZ 6

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Printed in ABS with general "medium quality" setting.

It may or may not require supports depending on your printer. I managed to print it without supports once, but that was an accident and may have been a fluke.

Sleeve Version Only

This is an improved version of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2422356 re-designed to the center spindle can print flat, which causes a big improvement in strength. But the stairstep pattern inside a horizontally printed tube won't perfectly seal.

push_0009b.stl includes a little shim that prints vertically - you're supposed to glue it inside the threaded section, for that perfect seal, since a horizontally printed part will be a bit rough inside.

Don't get it upside down, the wide end of the flange should point towards the ball bearing holes. Wipe up any excess glue.

Non-Sleeve Version Only

This is an improved version of https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2422356 re-designed to the center spindle can print flat, which causes a big improvement in strength. But the stairstep pattern inside a horizontally-printed tube won't seal perfectly. Paint it with ABS glue to get a shiny surface which will work better.

Both Versions

Paint a ring of ABS glue on the very end of the threaded section, to get a shiny surface that won't leak when screwed to a hose.

Ream out the holes in the center part until the BB's can just barely stick through the side, but not so much that they fall through. The locking sleeve can now be slid atop as an extremely tight fit, becoming loose again (though nearly unremovable) once the balls are fitting into the locking grooves.

The locking grooves hold the BB's fast when the sleeve is in the locked position, preventing the other half of the quick-connect from leaving.

Like most garden hose things, use proper hose washers to prevent leaks.

As usual, sources at my site: http://burningsmell.org/3d/pushfit/
